<TITLE> HC lifts ban of 5 milk powder brands </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 7 (bdnews24.com)The High Court on Wednesday withdrew the sale and display embargo on five foreign brands of powdered milkDano, Red Cow, Diploma, Nido and Anleneafter the World Health Organisation said European tests showed none exceed harmful levels of melamine. The HC bench of justices Syed Mahmud Hossain and Kamrul Islam Siddiqui gave the order on a report from the World Health Organisation submitted by the government on Tuesday. The tests showed that levels of melamine in the five brands of milk powder "did not exceed 0.1 ppm (parts per million)", said WHO in its report to the health minsitry. The report also mentioned that WHO "recently recommended that melamine residual levels in infant formula powder should not exceed 1ppm." The HC on Oct 23 it ordered the government to take immediate measures in banning display and sale of eight foreign milk powder brands suspected of melamine contamination including Australia's Diploma and Red Cow, Denmark's Dano Full Cream, China's Yashli-1, Yashli- 2 and Sweet Baby, and New Zealand's Nido Fortified Instant and Anlene. On Nov 10, it directed the government to collect samples of all brands of powder milk available in the market for testing and submitting the reports to the court. The HC on Wednesday also ordered tests of 28 other milk brands in the market to be submitted by the government within six weeks. After the HC ruling, barrister Rokanuddin Mahmud, lawyer for Nido, told bdnews24.com that there was no further bar to the sale and display of the five brands of foreign milk powder. bdnew
